query.result:
**English:**
1 The concubine of ancient Tithonus 2 was already turning white on the eastern balcony, 3 out of the arms of her sweet lover;
4 her forehead was shining with gems, 5 set in the figure of the cold animal 6 that strikes people with its tail;
7 and night, with the steps with which it ascends, 8 had taken two in the place where we were, 9 and was already lowering its wings for the third;
10 when I, who had with me some of Adam’s nature, 11 overcome by sleep, bowed down on the grass 12 where all five of us were sitting.
**Cornish:**
1 An gonkubin a’n Tithonus koth 2 a wra dalleth gwynn war an balji a’n est, 3 a-ves an brassa’v kar a’y huni kar.
4 Gwenn o jemyow o wra y hon tal, 5 set yn furv an eneval koth, 6 henna a wra’n fordh an dus a wra’n golpya an dus.
7 Ha’n nos, gans an passya henna a wra dalleth, 8 a wra gwres dhemedh y’n le a wra’n ni, 9 ha’n tresya a wra dalleth pleytya y eskel.
10 Pan vyn, a wra gans an rann a Adam, 11 gorholyes gans an kows, war an gemm a’n eneval 12 le may peswar oll a wra sedhes.

